Design tokens > JSON (create a new package: packages/tokens) > mapping to project 
Connector endpoint > platform refinement> Standardized formats (like W3C) 
by adding a new output configuration to Style Dictionary > You can easily add more platforms (iOS, Android)  
The "Adapter" Pattern (in packages/logic) - Define Interfaces in logic and inject the Implementation from the apps/.Example: logic defines AuthStore, but powerstarter (Web) passes it a Browser-storage implementation, while a future Mobile App passes it a Secure-Store implementation.  
Dependency Injection for Services - a way to "plug" services into your UI components. A React component in packages/ui shouldn't know how to call the API; it should just use a hook.  
Edge-Compatible Contracts (packages/contracts) - Ensure your contracts (Zod schemas) are strictly separated from your db (Prisma models). This allows your Frontend to validate data before it even hits the heavy Database layer, saving execution time and cost 
Automated "Internal" Versioning - As the repo grows, apps/trt might need logic version 1.0, while powerstarter is ready for 2.0. The Need: Managing manual version bumps in package.json across 10 packages is a nightmare. The Fix: Add Changesets. It automates the versioning and changelog generation for your internal packages, ensuring turbo always knows exactly what changed and what to rebuild. 
 
